<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Makah Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Hohoeapbess</font></U></B></I> 
(also spelled Ho-ho-e-ap-bess, or the Two Men Who Changed Things):
Twin Transformer characters, brothers of the sun and moon, who brought balance to the
world by using their powers to change people, animals, and the landscape into the forms they have today.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Raven</font></U></B></I>: 
Raven is the culture hero of the Makah and other Northwest Coast tribes.
He is a benevolent figure who helps the people,
but at the same time, he is also a trickster spirit and many Raven stories have to do with
his frivolous or poorly thought out behavior getting him into trouble.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Basket Ogress</font></U></B></I>
(Sxwayo'k!u, Sxwaysh'klu, or Sxwayok in the Makah language):
A giant cannibal monster who catches human children and carries them off in her enormous pack basket.

<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Makah Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/created.htm
">When the Animals and Birds Were Created</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Makah creation myth about Two-Men-Who-Changed-Things.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.kstrom.net/isk/stories/baskmaka.html
">Children Stolen by Cannibal Basket Woman</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Makah version of a classic Northwest Coast story about a child who defeats an ogress.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://www.usgs.gov/centers/pcmsc/science/native-american-legends-tsunamis-pacific-northwest?qt-science_center_objects=0#qt-science_center_objects
">Makah Tsunami Legend</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Makah legend about a massive tidal wave.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20080608234902/http://www.ess.washington.edu/SEIS/PNSN/HIST_CAT/STORIES/DRAFT2/quileute.html
">Weather Myths of Cascadia</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Stories from the <A HREF="http://www.native-languages.org/quileute.htm">Quileute</a>, 
<A HREF="http://www.native-languages.org/klallam.htm">Klallam</a>, and Makah tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/aurora.htm
">Legends and Folklore of the Northern Lights</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Aurora Borealis stories from the <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/inuktitut.htm">Inuit</a>,
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/kwakiutl.htm">Kwakiutl</a>, 
and Makah tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://www.gatheringthestories.org/2013/10/25/wah-tee-tas-dwarfs-of-cascadia/
">Little People of Oregon and Washington</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Stories about the legendary little people of the Makah and other Northwestern tribes.
<BR>

<H2><U>
<a name="books">Recommended Books on Makah Mythology</a>
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520239261/natilangofthe-20
">Indian Legends of the Pacific Northwest</a>:</B> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Collection of legends and folktales from the Makah and other northwestern tribes.
